                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d65">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/681: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-02-26T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 26, 1936—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>47. Your 106, February 25, 11 p.m. We offer no objection to the French suggestion
                    that four powers now in conference enter into a treaty and for British to enter
                    into bilateral treaty with Germany. You should make it clear, however, that the
                    purpose of the American mission is to extend existing Washington and London
                    treaties which included five original powers and that the United States takes no
                    part in a British, French, Italian arrangement by which a bilateral treaty would
                    be made to include Germany—this being essentially a European problem.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
